            "id": "https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-cpm-80-22/",
            "url": "https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-cpm-80-22/",
            "title": "How to experience CP/M-80 2.2?",
            "summary": "In the last post, we saw how to experience CP/M-80 1.4. For that and 86-DOS, we used a special emulator.",
            "content_html": "<p>In the last post, we saw <a href=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-cpm-80-14/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">how to experience CP/M-80 1.4</a>. For that and 86-DOS, we used a special emulator. For CP/M-80 2.2, there are 3 options. In this tutorial we are going to use the same emulator we used for the previous tutorials. You can download the emulator package from here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://archive.org/download/cpm-80-v2.2-linux/CPM80v2.2onlinux.tar.xz\">CP/M-80 2.2 for Linux</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://archive.org/download/cpm-80-v2.2-windows/CPM80v2.2onwindows.zip\">CP/M-80 2.2 for Windows</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Using CP/M-80 2.2</h1>\n<p>It is very easy to start using CP/M-80 2.2. On Linux, extract the above archive and right click on the cpm2.sh file and choose \"Run as a Program\" or run the shell file the way you run any other shell file. On Windows, extract the above archive and double click the Runme.bat file. The Virtual Machine will start.</p>\n<figure class=\"post__image post__image--center\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/CPM-80-2.2-1.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw\" srcset=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/responsive/CPM-80-2.2-1-xs.png 300w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/responsive/CPM-80-2.2-1-sm.png 480w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/responsive/CPM-80-2.2-1-md.png 768w\"  alt=\"CP/M-80 v2.2 emulator\" width=\"834\" height=\"630\"></figure>You can enter the DIR command to see a list of files.</p>\n<figure class=\"post__image post__image--center\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/CPM-80-2.2-2.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw\" srcset=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/responsive/CPM-80-2.2-2-xs.png 300w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/responsive/CPM-80-2.2-2-sm.png 480w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/5/responsive/CPM-80-2.2-2-md.png 768w\"  alt=\"CP/M-80 2.2 list of files\" width=\"834\" height=\"630\"></figure>That's it! We used CP/M-80 2.2, an operating system launched in 1982 after 40 years (at the time of writing this tutorial).</p>\n<h1>Manuals</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20220221170434/http://www.cpm.z80.de/randyfiles/DRI/CPM_2_0_Interface_Guide.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M 2.0 Interface Guide</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20220221170433/http://www.cpm.z80.de/randyfiles/DRI/CPM_2_0_System_Alteration_Guide.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M 2.0 System Alteration Guide</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20220324101601/http://www.cpm.z80.de/randyfiles/DRI/CPM_2_0_UG_for_CPM_1_4_Users.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M 2.0 User's Guide for CP/M 1.4 Users</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20200215062937/http://www.cpm.z80.de/manuals/CPMUserMan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M User Manual</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20220121011443/http://www.cpm.z80.de/manuals/cpm22-m.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M 2.2 MANUAL</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20220324101643/http://www.cpm.z80.de/manuals/SC-CPM.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M Reference Manual</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Related Pages</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CP/M\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Wikipedia</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cpm.z80.de/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Unofficial CP/M Web site</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://z80.de/ehome.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Gaby's Homepage for CP/M and Computer History</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.retroarchive.org/cpm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Commercial CP/M Software (Retro Archive)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://z80.de/ecpmlink.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">A lots of other links</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Credits</h1>\n<p>The emulator which is linked above was created by <a href=\"mailto:peter.schorn@acm.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Peter Schorn</a>. You can visit <a href=\"https://schorn.ch/altair.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">his website</a> to download the original emulator and lots of other software.</p>",
