            "id": "https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-cpm-80-14/",
            "url": "https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-cpm-80-14/",
            "title": "How to experience CP/M-80 1.4?",
            "summary": "In the last post, we saw how to experience 86-DOS. 86-DOS was a clone of CP/M. In this tutorial, we&hellip;",
            "content_html": "<p>In the last post, we saw <a href=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-86-dos/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">how to experience 86-DOS</a>. 86-DOS was a clone of CP/M. In this tutorial, we are going to use CP/M 1.4. Like 86-DOS, it also requires a special emulator which can be downloaded from here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/CPM80v1.4onlinux.tar.xz\">CP/M-80 1.4 for Linux</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/CPM80v1.4onwindows.zip\">CP/M-80 1.4 for Windows</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Using CP/M-80 1.4</h1>\n<p>It is very easy to start using CP/M-80 1.4. On Linux, extract the above archive and right click on the cpm1.sh file and choose \"Run as a Program\" or run the shell file the way you run any other shell file. On Windows, extract the above archive and double click the Runme.bat file. The Virtual Machine will start.</p>\n<figure class=\"post__image post__image--center\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/CPM-80-1.4-1.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw\" srcset=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/responsive/CPM-80-1.4-1-xs.png 300w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/responsive/CPM-80-1.4-1-sm.png 480w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/responsive/CPM-80-1.4-1-md.png 768w\"  alt=\"CP/M-80 1.4 emulator screenshot\" width=\"834\" height=\"630\"></figure>You can enter the DIR command to see a list of files.</p>\n<figure class=\"post__image post__image--center\"><img loading=\"lazy\"  src=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/CPM-80-1.4-2.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw\" srcset=\"https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/responsive/CPM-80-1.4-2-xs.png 300w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/responsive/CPM-80-1.4-2-sm.png 480w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/4/responsive/CPM-80-1.4-2-md.png 768w\"  alt=\"CP/M-80 1.4 DIR command screenshot\" width=\"834\" height=\"630\"></figure>\n<p>That's it! We used CP/M-80 1.4, an operating system launched in 1982 after 40 years (at the time of writing this tutorial).</p>\n<h1>Manuals</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20200215063155/http://www.cpm.z80.de/manuals/cpm13int.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M 1.3 Introduction</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20210912191531/http://www.cpm.z80.de/randyfiles/DRI/CPM_1_4_Interface_Guide.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M 1.4 Interface Guide</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20220324101539/http://www.cpm.z80.de/randyfiles/DRI/CPM_1_4_System_Alteration_Guide.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">CP/M 1.4 System Alteration Guide</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20220324101529/http://www.cpm.z80.de/randyfiles/DRI/Intro_to_CPM_Feat_and_Facilities.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Introduction to CP/M Features and Facilities (CP/M 1.4)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20200215062947/http://www.cpm.z80.de/manuals/CPM_SummaryGuide.pdf\" target=\"null\">CP/M Summary Guide (CP/M 1.4)</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Related Pages</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CP/M\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Wikipedia</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cpm.z80.de/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Unofficial CP/M Web site</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://z80.de/ehome.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Gaby's Homepage for CP/M and Computer History</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.retroarchive.org/cpm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Commercial CP/M Software (Retro Archive)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://z80.de/ecpmlink.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">A lots of other links</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Credits</h1>\n<p>The emulator which is linked above was created by <a href=\"mailto:peter.schorn@acm.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Peter Schorn</a>. You can visit <a href=\"https://schorn.ch/altair.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">his website</a> to download the original emulator and lots of other software.</p>",
